{"title_page": "Elizabeth J. Perry", "text_new": "'''Elizabeth J. Perry''', [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]] ({{zh|t=\u88f4\u5b9c\u7406|p=P\u00e9i Y\u00edl\u01d0}}; born 9 September 1948) is an American scholar of Chinese politics and [[Chinese history|history]] at [[Harvard University]], where she is the Henry Rosovsky Professor of Government and Director of the [[Harvard-Yenching Institute]]. She is a fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amacad.org/person/elizabeth-j-perry|title=Elizabeth J. Perry|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref> a corresponding fellow of the [[British Academy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/elizabeth-perry-FBA|title=Professor Elizabeth Perry FBA|publisher=British Academy|accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref> a recipient of a Guggenheim Fellowship,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/elizabeth-j-perry/|title=Elizabeth J. Perry|publisher=John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref> and served as Director of Harvard's [[Fairbank Center for East Asian Research]] from 1999 to 2003 and as President of the [[Association for Asian Studies]] in 2007.\n\n== Life and career ==\nPerry was born in [[Shanghai]], shortly before the [[Chinese Communist Revolution]], to American missionary parents who were professors at [[St. John's University (Shanghai)|St. John's University]]. She grew up in [[Tokyo]], Japan in the 1950s and participated in protests against the [[US-Japan Mutual Security Treaty]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Perry|first=Elizabeth J.|last2=Lu|first2=Hanchao|date=2015|title=Narrating the Past to Interpret the Present: A Conversation with Elizabeth J. Perry|url=https://dash.harvard.edu/handle/1/30820522|journal=The Chinese Historical Review|language=en-US|doi=10.1179/1547402X15Z.00000000051|issn=1547-402X}}</ref>\n\nShe returned to the United States and attended [[William Smith College]], where she earned her B.A. ''summa cum laude'' in 1969.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hws.edu/news/alum_pub.aspx|title=HWS: Alumni/ae Publications|website=Hobart and William Smith Colleges|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> In 1978, she received her Ph.D. in political science from the [[University of Michigan]] where her disserttion advisors included [[Michel Oksenberg]], [[Norma Diamond]], [[Albert Feuerwerker]], and [[Allen Whiting]].{{sfnb|Perry|1980|p=x}}  Her doctoral thesis explored the tradition of peasant rebellions of the [[Huaibei]] region of North China and the Communist Revolution.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepaper.cn/newsDetail_forward_1541086|title=\u6211\u7684\u8001\u5e08\u8521\u5c11\u537f\uff0c\u4e00\u4f4d\u4e2d\u56fd\u9876\u5c16\u7684\u793e\u4f1a\u53f2\u5b66\u5bb6|author=Elizabeth J. Perry (Pei Yili)|date=2016-10-24|website=The Paper|trans-title=My teacher Cai Shaoqing, a top Chinese scholar of social history|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\nPerry took her first teaching job at the [[University of Arizona]] before becoming an assistant, then associate  professor at the [[University of Washington]] (1978-1990); she the taught at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] as Robson Professor of Political Science, 1990-1997 before moving to Harvard.{{sfnb|Harvard University|2020}}\n\nWhen China and the US resumed academic exchange in 1979, she spent a year at [[Nanjing University]] as a visiting scholar, researching [[Chinese secret societies]] under [[Cai Shaoqing]] and the [[Taiping Rebellion]] under {{ill|Mao Jiaqi|zh|\u8305\u5bb6\u7426}}.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n==Scholarship and changing views==\nPerry's research focuses on the history of the Chinese revolution and its implications for contemporary politics. Although she earned all her degrees in political science, much of her research focuses on history and its links to contemporary issues. She observes that contemporary China consciously sees itself as an outgrowth of its long history, and Chinese political leaders are keenly aware of history, even if they may misunderstand it. As a result, history is highly consequential in the study of contemporary politics.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe had been sympathetic with the [[Cultural Revolution]] as a student, and joined the [[Committee of Concerned Asian Scholars]], a group that opposed American involvement in the Vietnam War. After witnessing the inequality in Communist China and hearing people's personal accounts about their suffering during the period, her views on the Chinese revolution and [[Maoism]] changed fundamentally.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Selected honors ==\nHer book, ''Shanghai on Strike: the Politics of Chinese Labor'' (1993) won the [[John K. Fairbank Prize]] from the [[American Historical Association]]. Her article \"From Mencius to Mao \u2013 and Now: Chinese Conceptions of Socioeconomic Rights\" (2008) won the Heinz Eulau Prize from the [[American Political Science Association]]. Perry received honorary doctorate degrees from Hobart and William Smith Colleges and from the [[Hong Kong University of Science and Technology]]. The Asian Studies Library at her undergraduate alma mater has been named in her honor. She also holds honorary professorships at eight major Chinese universities.\n\n==Selected books==\n*{{cite|first= Elizabeth J.|last= Perry|title=Rebels and Revolutionaries in North China, 1845\u20131945 |publisher= Stanford University Press|year= 1980|ref= harv}})\n*Chinese Perspectives on the Nien Rebellion (M.E. Sharpe, 1981)\n*The Political Economy of Reform in Post-Mao China (Harvard, 1985)\n*Popular Protest and Political Culture in Modern China (Westview, 1992)\n*Shanghai on Strike (Stanford, 1993)\n*Urban Spaces in Contemporary China: The Potential for Autonomy and Community in Chinese Cities (Cambridge, 1995)\n*Putting Class in Its Place: Worker Identities in East Asia (UC Berkeley, 1996)\n*Proletarian Power: Shanghai in the Cultural Revolution (Westview, 1997)\n*Danwei: The Changing Chinese Workplace in Historical and Comparative Perspective (M.E. Sharpe, 1997)\n*Chinese Society: Change, Conflict, and Resistance (Routledge, 2000)\n*Silence and Voice in the Study of Contentious Politics (Cambridge, 2001)\n*Challenging the Mandate of Heaven: Social Protest and State Power in China (M.E. Sharpe, 2002)\n*Changing Meanings of Citizenship in Modern China (Harvard, 2002)\n*Patrolling the Revolution: Worker Militias, Citizenship and the Chinese State (Rowman & Littlefield, 2005)\n*Grassroots Political Reform in Contemporary China (Harvard, 2007)\n*Mao's Invisible Hand: The Political Foundations of Adaptive Governanace in China (Harvard, 2011)\n*Anyuan: Mining China's revolutionary tradition (California, 2012)\n*Growing Pains in a Rising China (Daedalus, 2014)\n*What is the Best Kind of History? (Zhejiang, 2015) [in Chinese]\n*Beyond Regimes: China and India Compared (Harvard, 2018)\n*Similarity Amidst Difference: Christian Colleges in Republican China (Zhejiang, 2019) [in Chinese]\n*Ruling by Other Means: State-Mobilized Movements (Cambridge, forthcoming)\n==Selected articles==\n* {{cite journal |last =Perry |first= Elizabeth J.  |authormask = 3|title =Moving the Masses: Emotion Work in the Chinese Revolution |journal =Mobilization: An International Journal |volume =7 |issue = 2 |pages =111-128 |publisher = |location = |date =2002 |language = |url = |jstor = |issn = |doi = |accessdate = |ref= none}}\n\n* {{cite journal |last =Perry |first= Elizabeth J.  |authormask = 3|title =Studying Chinese Politics: Farewell to Revolution? |journal =The China Journal |volume= |issue = 57 |pages =1-22 |publisher = |location = |date =2007 |language = |url = |jstor = |issn = |doi = |accessdate = |ref= harv}}\n\n*{{cite journal |last =Perry |first= Elizabeth J.  |authormask = 3|title =Reclaiming the Chinese Revolution |journal =Journal of Asian Studies |volume =67 |issue = 4 |pages =1147-1164 |publisher = |location = |date =2008 |language = |url = |jstor = |issn = |doi = 10.1017/S0021911808001733 |accessdate = |ref= harv}} .  Chinese versions in QINGHUA XUEBAO (2012) and in Madeleine Yue Dong, ed., MAJOR WESTERN SCHOLARSHIP ON CHINESE HISTORY (Shanghai, 2010).\n* {{citation | first1= | last1 =Perry, Elizabeth J. |authormask=3|last2=Li |first2=Xun | chapter= Revolutionary Rudeness: The Language of Red Guards and Rebel Workers in China's Cultural Revolution |title= Twentieth Century China|volume= | series = | volume = | editor-first = | editor-last =Wasserstrom, Jeffrey N. | location = London; New York| publisher =Routledge | year =2003 | isbn = |url= |ref = harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last =Perry, Elizabeth J.  |first = |authormask = 3|title =Chinese Conceptions of \u201cRights\u201d: From Mencius to Mao\u2014and Now |journal =Perspectives on Politics |volume =6 |issue = 1 |pages =37-50 |publisher = |location = |date =2008 |language = |url = |jstor = |issn = |doi = 10.1017/S1537592708080055 |accessdate = |ref= none}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{cite|title= Elizabeth J Perry (Curriculum Vitae)|last= Harvard University| url=https://scholar.harvard.edu/elizabethperry/curriculum-vitae|year=2020|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Association for Asian Studies presidents}}\n{{FBA 2016}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perry, Elizabeth J.}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Washington faculty]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:American sinologists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Historians of Asia]]\n[[Category:American women historians]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Association for Asian Studies]]\n[[Category:Children of American missionaries in China]]\n[[Category:Corresponding Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Women orientalists]]\n[[Category:Historians from Shanghai]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in China]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:Hobart and William Smith Colleges alumni]]\n", "text_old": "'''Elizabeth J. Perry''', [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]] ({{zh|t=\u88f4\u5b9c\u7406|p=P\u00e9i Y\u00edl\u01d0}}; born 9 September 1948) is an American scholar of Chinese politics and [[Chinese history|history]] at [[Harvard University]], where she is the Henry Rosovsky Professor of Government and Director of the [[Harvard-Yenching Institute]]. She is a fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amacad.org/person/elizabeth-j-perry|title=Elizabeth J. Perry|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences|accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref> a corresponding fellow of the [[British Academy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/elizabeth-perry-FBA|title=Professor Elizabeth Perry FBA|publisher=British Academy|accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref> a recipient of a Guggenheim Fellowship,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gf.org/fellows/all-fellows/elizabeth-j-perry/|title=Elizabeth J. Perry|publisher=John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref> and served as Director of Harvard's [[Fairbank Center for East Asian Research]] from 1999 to 2003 and as President of the [[Association for Asian Studies]] in 2007.\n\n== Life and career ==\nPerry was born in [[Shanghai]], shortly before the [[Chinese Communist Revolution]], to American missionary parents who were professors at [[St. John's University (Shanghai)|St. John's University]]. She grew up in [[Tokyo]], Japan in the 1950s and participated in protests against the [[US-Japan Mutual Security Treaty]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Perry|first=Elizabeth J.|last2=Lu|first2=Hanchao|date=2015|title=Narrating the Past to Interpret the Present: A Conversation with Elizabeth J. Perry|url=https://dash.harvard.edu/handle/1/30820522|journal=The Chinese Historical Review|language=en-US|doi=10.1179/1547402X15Z.00000000051|issn=1547-402X}}</ref>\n\nShe returned to the United States and attended [[William Smith College]], where she earned her B.A. ''summa cum laude'' in 1969.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hws.edu/news/alum_pub.aspx|title=HWS: Alumni/ae Publications|website=Hobart and William Smith Colleges|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref> In 1978, she received her Ph.D. in political science from the [[University of Michigan]] where her disserttion advisors included [[Michel Oksenberg]], [[Norma Diamond]], [[Albert Feuerwerker]], and [[Allen Whiting]].{{sfnb|Perry|1980|p=x}}  Her doctoral thesis explored the tradition of peasant rebellions of the [[Huaibei]] region of North China and the Communist Revolution.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepaper.cn/newsDetail_forward_1541086|title=\u6211\u7684\u8001\u5e08\u8521\u5c11\u537f\uff0c\u4e00\u4f4d\u4e2d\u56fd\u9876\u5c16\u7684\u793e\u4f1a\u53f2\u5b66\u5bb6|author=Elizabeth J. Perry (Pei Yili)|date=2016-10-24|website=The Paper|trans-title=My teacher Cai Shaoqing, a top Chinese scholar of social history|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\nPerry took her first teaching job at the [[University of Arizona]] before becoming an assistant, then associate  professor at the [[University of Washington]] (1978-1990); she the taught at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] as Robson Professor of Political Science, 1990-1997 before moving to Harvard.{{sfnb|Harvard University|2020}}\n\nWhen China and the US resumed academic exchange in 1979, she spent a year at [[Nanjing University]] as a visiting scholar, researching [[Chinese secret societies]] under [[Cai Shaoqing]] and the [[Taiping Rebellion]] under {{ill|Mao Jiaqi|zh|\u8305\u5bb6\u7426}}.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n==Scholarship and changing views==\nPerry's research focuses on the history of the Chinese revolution and its implications for contemporary politics. Although she earned all her degrees in political science, much of her research focuses on history and its links to contemporary issues. She observes that contemporary China consciously sees itself as an outgrowth of its long history, and Chinese political leaders are keenly aware of history, even if they may misunderstand it. As a result, history is highly consequential in the study of contemporary politics.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nShe had been sympathetic with the [[Cultural Revolution]] as a student, and joined the [[Committee of Concerned Asian Scholars]], a group that opposed American involvement in the Vietnam War. After witnessing the inequality in Communist China and hearing people's personal accounts about their suffering during the period, her views on the Chinese revolution and [[Maoism]] changed fundamentally.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Selected honors ==\nHer book, ''Shanghai on Strike: the Politics of Chinese Labor'' (1993) won the [[John K. Fairbank Prize]] from the [[American Historical Association]]. Her article \"From Mencius to Mao \u2013 and Now: Chinese Conceptions of Socioeconomic Rights\" (2008) won the Heinz Eulau Prize from the [[American Political Science Association]]. Perry received honorary doctorate degrees from Hobart and William Smith Colleges and from the [[Hong Kong University of Science and Technology]]. The Asian Studies Library at her undergraduate alma mater has been named in her honor. She also holds honorary professorships at eight major Chinese universities.\n\n==Selected books==\n*{{cite|first= Elizabeth J.|last= Perry|title=Rebels and Revolutionaries in North China, 1845\u20131945 |publisher= Stanford University Press|year= 1980|ref= harv}})\n*Chinese Perspectives on the Nien Rebellion (M.E. Sharpe, 1981)\n*The Political Economy of Reform in Post-Mao China (Harvard, 1985)\n*Popular Protest and Political Culture in Modern China (Westview, 1992)\n*Shanghai on Strike (Stanford, 1993)\n*Urban Spaces in Contemporary China: The Potential for Autonomy and Community in Chinese Cities (Cambridge, 1995)\n*Putting Class in Its Place: Worker Identities in East Asia (UC Berkeley, 1996)\n*Proletarian Power: Shanghai in the Cultural Revolution (Westview, 1997)\n*Danwei: The Changing Chinese Workplace in Historical and Comparative Perspective (M.E. Sharpe, 1997)\n*Chinese Society: Change, Conflict, and Resistance (Routledge, 2000)\n*Silence and Voice in the Study of Contentious Politics (Cambridge, 2001)\n*Challenging the Mandate of Heaven: Social Protest and State Power in China (M.E. Sharpe, 2002)\n*Changing Meanings of Citizenship in Modern China (Harvard, 2002)\n*Patrolling the Revolution: Worker Militias, Citizenship and the Chinese State (Rowman & Littlefield, 2005)\n*Grassroots Political Reform in Contemporary China (Harvard, 2007)\n*Mao's Invisible Hand: The Political Foundations of Adaptive Governanace in China (Harvard, 2011)\n*Anyuan: Mining China's revolutionary tradition (California, 2012)\n*Growing Pains in a Rising China (Daedalus, 2014)\n*What is the Best Kind of History? (Zhejiang, 2015) [in Chinese]\n*Beyond Regimes: China and India Compared (Harvard, 2018)\n*Similarity Amidst Difference: Christian Colleges in Republican China (Zhejiang, 2019) [in Chinese]\n*Ruling by Other Means: State-Mobilized Movements (Cambridge, forthcoming)\n==Selected articles==\n* {{cite journal |last =Perry |first= Elizabeth J.  |authormask = 3|title =Moving the Masses: Emotion Work in the Chinese Revolution |journal =Mobilization: An International Journal |volume =7 |issue = 2 |pages =111-128 |publisher = |location = |date =2002 |language = |url = |jstor = |issn = |doi = |accessdate = |ref= none}}\n\n* {{cite journal |last =Perry |first= Elizabeth J.  |authormask = 3|title =Studying Chinese Politics: Farewell to Revolution? |journal =The China Journal |volume= |issue = 57 |pages =1-22 |publisher = |location = |date =2007 |language = |url = |jstor = |issn = |doi = |accessdate = |ref= harv}}\n\n*{{cite journal |last =Perry |first= Elizabeth J.  |authormask = 3|title =Reclaiming the Chinese Revolution |journal =Journal of Asian Studies |volume =67 |issue = 4 |pages =1147-1164 |publisher = |location = |date =2008 |language = |url = |jstor = |issn = |doi = 10.1017/S0021911808001733 |accessdate = |ref= harv}} .  Chinese versions in QINGHUA XUEBAO (2012) and in Madeleine Yue Dong, ed., MAJOR WESTERN SCHOLARSHIP ON CHINESE HISTORY (Shanghai, 2010).\n* {{citation | first1= | last1 =Perry, Elizabeth J. |authormask=3|last2=Li |first2=Xun | chapter= Revolutionary Rudeness: The Language of Red Guards and Rebel Workers in China's Cultural Revolution |title= Twentieth Century China|volume= | series = | volume = | editor-first = | editor-last =Wasserstrom, Jeffrey N. | location = London; New York| publisher =Routledge | year =2003 | isbn = |url= |ref = harv}}\n*{{cite journal |last =Perry, Elizabeth J.  |first = |authormask = 3|title =Chinese Conceptions of \u201cRights\u201d: From Mencius to Mao\u2014and Now |journal =Perspectives on Politics |volume =6 |issue = 1 |pages =37-50 |publisher = |location = |date =2008 |language = |url = https://www.cambridge.org/core/article/chinese-conceptions-of-rights-from-mencius-to-maoand-now/28003ACD49D65DA3DF57312A126B569B |jstor = |issn = |doi = 10.1017/S1537592708080055 |accessdate = |ref= none}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{cite|title= Elizabeth J Perry (Curriculum Vitae)|last= Harvard University| url=https://scholar.harvard.edu/elizabethperry/curriculum-vitae|year=2020|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Association for Asian Studies presidents}}\n{{FBA 2016}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Perry, Elizabeth J.}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Arizona faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Washington faculty]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:American sinologists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Historians of Asia]]\n[[Category:American women historians]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Association for Asian Studies]]\n[[Category:Children of American missionaries in China]]\n[[Category:Corresponding Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Women orientalists]]\n[[Category:Historians from Shanghai]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in China]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:Hobart and William Smith Colleges alumni]]\n", "name_user": "CWH", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSelected articles:remove bad link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elizabeth_J._Perry"}
{"title_page": "Stylish", "text_new": "{{About|the browser extension|the Loona song|+ + (EP)}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox Software\n| name                   = Stylish\n| logo                   = Stylish SVG Logo.svg\n| screenshot             = Stylish screenshot.png\n| screenshot alt         = Editing a website style with Stylish\n| caption                = Screenshot of Stylish\n| collapsible            = yes\n| author                 = Jason Barnabe\n| developer              = [[SimilarWeb]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcement to the Community |last=Hindman |first=Justin |date=January 3, 2017 |website=userstyles.org |url=https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/53233/announcement-to-the-community |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105193347/https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/53233/announcement-to-the-community |archive-date=January 5, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| ver layout             = stacked\n| latest_release_version = {{Multiple releases\n | branch1    = Firefox\n | version1   = 3.1.8\n | date1      = {{release date and age|2018|07|28}}<ref>{{cite web \n | title      = Stylish - Custom themes for any website Version History\n | url        = https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/stylish/versions/\n | website    = addons.mozilla.org\n}}</ref>\n\n | branch2    = Chrome\n | version2   = 2.0.9\n | date2      = {{release date and age|2018|12|23}}<ref>{{cite web\n | title      = Stylish - Custom themes for any website\n | url        = https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/stylish-custom-themes-for/fjnbnpbmkenffdnngjfgmeleoegfcffe\n | website    = [[Chrome Web Store]]\n}}</ref>\n\n | branch3    = Opera\n | version3   = 1.3.1\n | date3      = {{release date and age|2015|05|05}}<ref>{{cite web\n | title      = Stylish extension - Opera Add-ons\n | url        = https://addons.opera.com/en-gb/extensions/details/stylish/?display=en&page=3\n | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180130203932/https://addons.opera.com/en-gb/extensions/details/stylish/?display=en&page=3\n | archive-date= January 30, 2018\n | url-status   = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n | branch4    = Safari\n | version4   = 2.1.0\n | date4      = {{release date and age|2018|06|29}}\n}}\n<!--2.0.7 (Firefox) {{release date and age|2016|08|09}}<ref>[https://addons.mozilla.org/firefox/addon/stylish/versions/ Stylish version history] on addons.mozilla.org.</ref>\n1.5.2 (Chrome) {{release date and age|2016|04|04}}<ref name=\"Stylish for Chrome\">{{cite web\n| title=Stylish\n| url=https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/stylish/fjnbnpbmkenffdnngjfgmeleoegfcffe\n| website=Chrome Web Store\n| accessdate=19 October 2016}}</ref><br />\n1.9.2 (Safari)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sobolev.us/stylish/ | title=Stylish for Safari | date=28 December 2011 | publisher=Vladimir Sobolev | accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref> {{release date and age|2016|09|05}}<ref>{{cite web|title=1.9.2 - 350d/stylish@ea6df1e|url=https://github.com/350d/stylish/commit/ea6df1e67cd9fa493884ae15969e79be603d0964|website=GitHub|accessdate=19 October 2016}}</ref><br />\n1.3.1 (Opera) {{release date and age|2015|05|05|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Stylish extension|url=https://addons.opera.com/en/extensions/details/stylish/|website=Opera add-ons|accessdate=20 October 2016}}</ref>-->\n| genre                  = [[Browser extension]]\n| repo                   = [https://github.com/stylish-userstyles/stylish Mozilla (XUL/XPCOM)]<br />\n[https://github.com/stylish-userstyles/stylish-chrome Chrome, Opera] <br />\n[https://github.com/350D/stylish Safari] <br />\n[https://github.com/gera2ld/Stylish-oex Opera 12 (Presto)]\n| license                = [[Freeware]]<br />\n| released = {{Start date and age|2005|10|09}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Stylish 0.1.1 Released [Oct 11] |author=np [Jason Barnabe] |website=[[MozillaZine]] |date=October 9, 2005 |url=http://forums.mozillazine.org/viewtopic.php?t=327735 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051210042217/http://forums.mozillazine.org/viewtopic.php?t=327735 |archive-date=December 10, 2005 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Stylish''' is a user style manager that can change the appearance of web pages in a user's browser without changing their content by including user-supplied [[Cascading Style Sheets|CSS style sheets]] with those supplied by the web site itself. The Stylish [[browser extension]] includes tools with which to write user styles, and can install user styles written by other Stylish users from a companion website. These user styles may be more or less selective, targeting just one web page, or all of the pages on a [[Domain name|domain]], or every page on the web.\n\nStylish was originally developed by Jason Barnabe as an [[XUL]]/[[XPCOM]] add-on for [[Mozilla]] [[Firefox]]. A [[Chrome extension]] followed in 2010,<ref>{{cite web |title=Stylish for Google Chrome |last=Barnabe |first=Jason |url=https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/17761/stylish-for-google-chrome |website=Userstyles.org |date=March 1, 2010}}</ref> which was released for [[Blink (web engine)|Blink]]-based [[Opera (web browser)|Opera]] 15 in 2013<ref>{{cite url |title=Stylish for Chrome and Opera (15+) 1.2b |last=Barnabe |first=Jason |date=July 3, 2013 |url=https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/36378/stylish-for-chrome-and-opera-15-1-2b |website=Userstyles.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Stylish extension - Opera add-ons |publisher=Opera Software ASA |url=https://addons.opera.com/en-gb/extensions/details/stylish/?display=en&page=3 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150425173412/https://addons.opera.com/en-gb/extensions/details/stylish/?display=en&page=3#c686335 |archive-date=April 25, 2013 |url-status=dead\n |postscript = . <br/> The oldest comment is dated July 26, 2013.\n}}</ref> and as a Firefox [[Features of Firefox#Electrolysis and WebExtensions|WebExtension]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=New version for Firefox |date=November 2, 2017 |website=userstyles.org |url=https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/60992/new-version-for-firefox |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226101549/https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/60992/new-version-for-firefox |archive-date=December 26, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |title=Stylish - Custom themes for any website Version History\n |website=Firefox Add-ons\n |publisher=Mozilla |url=https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/stylish/versions/\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512101058/https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/stylish/versions/\n |archive-date=May 12, 2018\n |url-status=dead\n |postscript  = . <br/> Version 3.0.1 is the first Stylish for Firefox WebExtension release; version 2.1.1 is the last Stylish XUL/XPCOM add-on release.\n}}</ref> Similar extensions for [[Safari (web browser)|Safari]]<ref name=\"stylish-safari\">{{cite web |title=Stylish for Safari |last=Sobolev |first=Vladimir |url=http://sobolev.us/stylish/ }}</ref> and for [[Presto (browser engine)|Presto]]-based Opera<ref name=\"stylish-presto\">{{cite web |title=Stylish for Opera |author=gera2ld |publisher=Opera Software ASA |date= |url=https://addons.opera.com/en/extensions/details/stylish-for-opera/ }}</ref> are distributed as 'Stylish' by other developers with Barnabe's approval.<ref>{{web cite |title=Stylish for Safari |last=Barnabe |first=Jason |website=userstyles.org |date=April 9, 2014 |url=https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/comment/87494/#Comment_87494 }}</ref><ref>{{web cite |title=Stylish for Opera! |last=Barnabe |first=Jason |date=January 1, 2013 |website=userstyles.org \n| url=https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/34075/stylish-for-opera }}</ref>\n\n==Technical details==\n\nUser styles are CSS code designed to alter the appearance of one, some, or all sites. Stylish for Firefox can additionally style the skin of the browser itself, but the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] version does not support this because the user interface is built in native Android code. The styles are applied only to the targets specified. Individual user styles can be enabled or disabled without having to restart the browser.\n\nUser styles are added to the CSS rules provided by the site, but can also override the site's styling (often requiring the <code>!important</code> keyword for each replacement rule). The most common uses are [[ad blocking]], applying a new color scheme, and eliminating unwanted page elements.<ref>\"[http://www.linux.com/archive/articles/61745 Make the whole Web look better with Stylish],\" Nathan Willis, Mon 7 May 2007.</ref>\n\nThere are three classes of user styles. Site styles change the appearance of a particular web site. Global styles change the appearance of all web sites. App styles change the appearance of the Firefox user interface, only supported on Firefox. It is similar to the <code>userChrome.css</code> CSS file used by Firefox and Mozilla-based browsers.\n\n==Privacy issues==\n\nSince January 2017, following the sale of Stylish to Israeli company [[SimilarWeb]], the extension has contained tracking functions that sends information on all visited URLs and HTTP requests, and information contained on search engine results pages, to SimilarWeb servers. In July 2018, after these issues were publicized by a software engineer, Stylish was pulled from both the [[Chrome Web Store]] and [[Mozilla Add-ons]], as well as being automatically uninstalled for all existing users.<ref name=\"ars-stylish-banned\">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2018/07/stylish-extension-with-2m-downloads-banished-for-tracking-every-site-visit/|title=\u201cStylish\u201d extension with 2M downloads banned for tracking every site visit|last=Goodin|first=Dan|date=2018-07-06|website=[[Ars Technica]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|accessdate=2018-07-06|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/use-this-popular-chrome-firefox-add-on-google-mozilla-just-banished-it/|title=Use this popular Chrome, Firefox browser add-on? Google, Mozilla just banished it|last=Tung|first=Liam|work=[[ZDNet]]|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en|date=2018-07-05|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"bleeping-stylish-pulled\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/software/chrome-and-firefox-pull-stylish-add-on-after-report-it-logged-browser-history/|title=Chrome and Firefox Pull Stylish Add-On After Report It Logged Browser History|work=[[Bleeping Computer]]|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-us|df=mdy-all|first=Catalin|last=Cimpanu|date=2018-07-04}}</ref>\n\n==Alternatives to Stylish==\nA [[userscript manager]] such as [[Greasemonkey]] or [[Tampermonkey]] can add a local style sheet to a web page by adding the style sheet content to an HTML {{code|lang=html|code=<style>}} tag and adding the tag to the page.<ref>{{cite book\n |title = 4.13. Adding CSS styles\n |last = Pilgrim |first= Mark\n |work  = Dive Into Greasemonkey\n |year  = 2005\n |url   = http://greasemonkey.win-start.de/patterns/add-css.html\n}}</ref> User styles from Userstyles.org can be downloaded as user scripts for use with a userscript manager.\n\nAlternative user style managers include Stylus<ref>https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/styl-us/</ref> and xStyle,<ref>https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/xstyle/</ref> which are derived from Stylish for Chrome,<ref>https://github.com/openstyles/stylus</ref><ref>https://github.com/FirefoxBar/xStyle</ref> aStyle,<ref>https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/astyle_easy/</ref> reStyle,<ref>https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/re-style/</ref> and Website Theme Manager.<ref>https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/website-theme-manager/</ref> [https://github.com/openstyles/stylus/wiki/Stylish-alternatives Stylus' GitHub page] contains a table showing alternatives to Stylish for several popular browsers.\n\nIn Firefox, user styles for web sites and browser chrome can be added to local files <code>userContent.css</code><ref>http://kb.mozillazine.org/UserContent.css</ref> or <code>userChrome.css</code>,<ref>http://kb.mozillazine.org/UserChrome.css</ref> respectively. As of Firefox 69, user must switch the <code>toolkit.legacyUserProfileCustomizations.stylesheets</code> preference to true in <code>about:config</code> in order to load these files.<ref>https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Archive/Mozilla/XUL/Tutorial/Modifying_the_Default_Skin</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}} \n\n[[Category:Firefox add-ons]]\n[[Category:Google Chrome extensions]]\n[[Category:Cascading Style Sheets]]\n[[Category:2005 software]]\n[[Category:Spyware]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the browser extension|the Loona song|+ + (EP)}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox Software\n| name                   = Stylish\n| logo                   = Stylish SVG Logo.svg\n| screenshot             = Stylish screenshot.png\n| screenshot alt         = Editing a website style with Stylish\n| caption                = Screenshot of Stylish\n| collapsible            = yes\n| author                 = Jason Barnabe\n| developer              = [[SimilarWeb]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Announcement to the Community |last=Hindman |first=Justin |date=January 3, 2017 |website=userstyles.org |url=https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/53233/announcement-to-the-community |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105193347/https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/53233/announcement-to-the-community |archive-date=January 5, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n| ver layout             = stacked\n| latest_release_version = {{Multiple releases\n | branch1    = Firefox\n | version1   = 3.1.8\n | date1      = {{release date and age|2018|07|28}}<ref>{{cite web \n | title      = Stylish - Custom themes for any website Version History\n | url        = https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/stylish/versions/\n | website    = addons.mozilla.org\n}}</ref>\n\n | branch2    = Chrome\n | version2   = 2.0.9\n | date2      = {{release date and age|2018|12|23}}<ref>{{cite web\n | title      = Stylish - Custom themes for any website\n | url        = https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/stylish-custom-themes-for/fjnbnpbmkenffdnngjfgmeleoegfcffe\n | website    = [[Chrome Web Store]]\n}}</ref>\n\n | branch3    = Opera\n | version3   = 1.3.1\n | date3      = {{release date and age|2015|05|05}}<ref>{{cite web\n | title      = Stylish extension - Opera Add-ons\n | url        = https://addons.opera.com/en-gb/extensions/details/stylish/?display=en&page=3\n | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180130203932/https://addons.opera.com/en-gb/extensions/details/stylish/?display=en&page=3\n | archive-date= January 30, 2018\n | url-status   = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n | branch4    = Safari\n | version4   = 2.1.0\n | date4      = {{release date and age|2018|06|29}}\n}}\n<!--2.0.7 (Firefox) {{release date and age|2016|08|09}}<ref>[https://addons.mozilla.org/firefox/addon/stylish/versions/ Stylish version history] on addons.mozilla.org.</ref>\n1.5.2 (Chrome) {{release date and age|2016|04|04}}<ref name=\"Stylish for Chrome\">{{cite web\n| title=Stylish\n| url=https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/stylish/fjnbnpbmkenffdnngjfgmeleoegfcffe\n| website=Chrome Web Store\n| accessdate=19 October 2016}}</ref><br />\n1.9.2 (Safari)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://sobolev.us/stylish/ | title=Stylish for Safari | date=28 December 2011 | publisher=Vladimir Sobolev | accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref> {{release date and age|2016|09|05}}<ref>{{cite web|title=1.9.2 - 350d/stylish@ea6df1e|url=https://github.com/350d/stylish/commit/ea6df1e67cd9fa493884ae15969e79be603d0964|website=GitHub|accessdate=19 October 2016}}</ref><br />\n1.3.1 (Opera) {{release date and age|2015|05|05|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Stylish extension|url=https://addons.opera.com/en/extensions/details/stylish/|website=Opera add-ons|accessdate=20 October 2016}}</ref>-->\n| genre                  = [[Browser extension]]\n| repo                   = [https://github.com/stylish-userstyles/stylish Mozilla (XUL/XPCOM)]<br />\n[https://github.com/stylish-userstyles/stylish-chrome Chrome, Opera] <br />\n[https://github.com/350D/stylish Safari] <br />\n[https://github.com/gera2ld/Stylish-oex Opera 12 (Presto)]\n| license                = [[Freeware]]<br />\n| released = {{Start date and age|2005|10|09}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Stylish 0.1.1 Released [Oct 11] |author=np [Jason Barnabe] |website=[[MozillaZine]] |date=October 9, 2005 |url=http://forums.mozillazine.org/viewtopic.php?t=327735 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051210042217/http://forums.mozillazine.org/viewtopic.php?t=327735 |archive-date=December 10, 2005 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Stylish''' is a user style manager that can change the appearance of web pages in a user's browser without changing their content by including user-supplied [[Cascading Style Sheets|CSS style sheets]] with those supplied by the web site itself. The Stylish [[browser extension]] includes tools with which to write user styles, and can install user styles written by other Stylish users from a companion website. These user styles may be more or less selective, targeting just one web page, or all of the pages on a [[Domain name|domain]], or every page on the web.\n\nStylish was originally developed by Jason Barnabe as an [[XUL]]/[[XPCOM]] add-on for [[Mozilla]] [[Firefox]]. A [[Chrome extension]] followed in 2010,<ref>{{cite web |title=Stylish for Google Chrome |last=Barnabe |first=Jason |url=https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/17761/stylish-for-google-chrome |website=Userstyles.org |date=March 1, 2010}}</ref> which was released for [[Blink (web engine)|Blink]]-based [[Opera (web browser)|Opera]] 15 in 2013<ref>{{cite url |title=Stylish for Chrome and Opera (15+) 1.2b |last=Barnabe |first=Jason |date=July 3, 2013 |url=https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/36378/stylish-for-chrome-and-opera-15-1-2b |website=Userstyles.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Stylish extension - Opera add-ons |publisher=Opera Software ASA |url=https://addons.opera.com/en-gb/extensions/details/stylish/?display=en&page=3 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150425173412/https://addons.opera.com/en-gb/extensions/details/stylish/?display=en&page=3#c686335 |archive-date=April 25, 2013 |url-status=dead\n |postscript = . <br/> The oldest comment is dated July 26, 2013.\n}}</ref> and as a Firefox [[Features of Firefox#Electrolysis and WebExtensions|WebExtension]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |title=New version for Firefox |date=November 2, 2017 |website=userstyles.org |url=https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/60992/new-version-for-firefox |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226101549/https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/60992/new-version-for-firefox |archive-date=December 26, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |title=Stylish - Custom themes for any website Version History\n |website=Firefox Add-ons\n |publisher=Mozilla |url=https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/stylish/versions/\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180512101058/https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/stylish/versions/\n |archive-date=May 12, 2018\n |url-status=dead\n |postscript  = . <br/> Version 3.0.1 is the first Stylish for Firefox WebExtension release; version 2.1.1 is the last Stylish XUL/XPCOM add-on release.\n}}</ref> Similar extensions for [[Safari (web browser)|Safari]]<ref name=\"stylish-safari\">{{cite web |title=Stylish for Safari |last=Sobolev |first=Vladimir |url=http://sobolev.us/stylish/ }}</ref> and for [[Presto (browser engine)|Presto]]-based Opera<ref name=\"stylish-presto\">{{cite web |title=Stylish for Opera |author=gera2ld |publisher=Opera Software ASA |date= |url=https://addons.opera.com/en/extensions/details/stylish-for-opera/ }}</ref> are distributed as 'Stylish' by other developers with Barnabe's approval.<ref>{{web cite |title=Stylish for Safari |last=Barnabe |first=Jason |website=userstyles.org |date=April 9, 2014 |url=https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/comment/87494/#Comment_87494 }}</ref><ref>{{web cite |title=Stylish for Opera! |last=Barnabe |first=Jason |date=January 1, 2013 |website=userstyles.org \n| url=https://forum.userstyles.org/discussion/34075/stylish-for-opera }}</ref>\n\n==Technical details==\n\nUser styles are CSS code designed to alter the appearance of one, some, or all sites. Stylish for Firefox can additionally style the skin of the browser itself, but the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] version does not support this because the user interface is built in native Android code. The styles are applied only to the targets specified. Individual user styles can be enabled or disabled without having to restart the browser.\n\nUser styles are added to the CSS rules provided by the site, but can also override the site's styling (often requiring the <code>!important</code> keyword for each replacement rule). The most common uses are [[ad blocking]], applying a new color scheme, and eliminating unwanted page elements.<ref>\"[http://www.linux.com/archive/articles/61745 Make the whole Web look better with Stylish],\" Nathan Willis, Mon 7 May 2007.</ref>\n\nThere are three classes of user styles. Site styles change the appearance of a particular web site. Global styles change the appearance of all web sites. App styles change the appearance of the Firefox user interface, only supported on Firefox. It is similar to the <code>userChrome.css</code> CSS file used by Firefox and Mozilla-based browsers.\n\n==Privacy issues==\n\nSince January 2017, following the sale of Stylish to Israeli company [[SimilarWeb]], the extension has contained tracking functions that sends information on all visited URLs and HTTP requests, and information contained on search engine results pages, to SimilarWeb servers. In July 2018, after these issues were publicized by a software engineer, Stylish was pulled from both the [[Chrome Web Store]] and [[Mozilla Add-ons]], as well as being automatically uninstalled for all existing users.<ref name=\"ars-stylish-banned\">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2018/07/stylish-extension-with-2m-downloads-banished-for-tracking-every-site-visit/|title=\u201cStylish\u201d extension with 2M downloads banned for tracking every site visit|last=Goodin|first=Dan|date=2018-07-06|website=[[Ars Technica]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|accessdate=2018-07-06|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/use-this-popular-chrome-firefox-add-on-google-mozilla-just-banished-it/|title=Use this popular Chrome, Firefox browser add-on? Google, Mozilla just banished it|last=Tung|first=Liam|work=[[ZDNet]]|access-date=2018-07-06|language=en|date=2018-07-05|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"bleeping-stylish-pulled\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/software/chrome-and-firefox-pull-stylish-add-on-after-report-it-logged-browser-history/|title=Chrome and Firefox Pull Stylish Add-On After Report It Logged Browser History|work=[[Bleeping Computer]]|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-us|df=mdy-all|first=Catalin|last=Cimpanu|date=2018-07-04}}</ref>\n\n==Alternatives to Stylish==\nA [[userscript manager]] such as [[Greasemonkey]] or [[Tampermonkey]] can add a local style sheet to a web page by adding the style sheet content to an HTML {{code|lang=html|code=<style>}} tag and adding the tag to the page.<ref>{{cite book\n |title = 4.13. Adding CSS styles\n |last = Pilgrim |first= Mark\n |work  = Dive Into Greasemonkey\n |year  = 2005\n |url   = http://greasemonkey.win-start.de/patterns/add-css.html\n}}</ref> User styles from Userstyles.org can be downloaded as user scripts for use with a userscript manager.\n\nAlternative user style managers include Stylus<ref>https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/styl-us/</ref> and xStyle,<ref>https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/xstyle/</ref> which are derived from Stylish for Chrome,<ref>https://github.com/openstyles/stylus</ref><ref>https://github.com/FirefoxBar/xStyle</ref> aStyle,<ref>https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/astyle_easy/</ref> reStyle,<ref>https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/re-style/</ref> and Website Theme Manager.<ref>https://addons.mozilla.org/en-US/firefox/addon/website-theme-manager/</ref>[https://github.com/openstyles/stylus/wiki/Stylish-alternatives Stylus' GitHub page] contains a table showing alternatives to Stylish for several popular browsers.\n\nIn Firefox, user styles for web sites and browser chrome can be added to local files <code>userContent.css</code><ref>http://kb.mozillazine.org/UserContent.css</ref> or <code>userChrome.css</code>,<ref>http://kb.mozillazine.org/UserChrome.css</ref> respectively. As of Firefox 69, user must switch the <code>toolkit.legacyUserProfileCustomizations.stylesheets</code> preference to true in <code>about:config</code> in order to load these files.<ref>https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Archive/Mozilla/XUL/Tutorial/Modifying_the_Default_Skin</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website}} \n\n[[Category:Firefox add-ons]]\n[[Category:Google Chrome extensions]]\n[[Category:Cascading Style Sheets]]\n[[Category:2005 software]]\n[[Category:Spyware]]\n", "name_user": "Sebastian Hudak", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAlternatives to Stylish:added space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stylish"}
